This section provides an overview of spatial operations on vector geographic data represented as simple features in the sf packag.

Subsetting

In this example, We will subset Newzealnd heights which are in Canterbury only. Canterbury area is defined as a subset from another data file of Newzealnd

Describing spatial relationships between objects

First will create 3 different objects to play with

# create a polygon
a_poly = st_polygon(list(rbind(c(-1, -1), c(1, -1), c(1, 1), c(-1, -1))))
a = st_sfc(a_poly)

# create a line
l_line = st_linestring(x = matrix(c(-1, -1, -0.5, 1), ncol = 2))
l = st_sfc(l_line)

# create points
p_matrix = matrix(c(0.5, 1, -1, 0, 0, 1, 0.5, 1), ncol = 2)
p_multi = st_multipoint(x = p_matrix)
p = st_cast(st_sfc(p_multi), "POINT")

plot(a,border = "blue")
plot(l,add=TRUE)
plot(p ,add = TRUE,col = "red")

###Is there an intersection using st_intersects function

##Is there an intersection between the polygon and the points?
st_intersects(p, a, sparse = FALSE)
##       [,1]
## [1,]  TRUE
## [2,]  TRUE
## [3,] FALSE
## [4,] FALSE

Is there points which do not intersect using st_disjoint()

st_disjoint(p, a, sparse = FALSE)[, 1]
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE
#note [, 1] converts the result into a vector

Are some objects completely within another object using st_within()

st_within(p, a, sparse = FALSE)[, 1]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE
#This applies only to the first object, as the other one which used to bet TRUE is only touching the polygon's border

Which points touch the border using st_touchs()

st_touches(p, a, sparse = FALSE)[, 1]
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE

Which objects are within specific distance from another object using st_is_within_distance

st_is_within_distance(p, a, dist = 0.9, sparse= FALSE)
##       [,1]
## [1,]  TRUE
## [2,]  TRUE
## [3,] FALSE
## [4,]  TRUE
#dist : distance threshold; geometry indexes with distances smaller or equal to this value are returned

Spatial joining

Spatial data joining relies on shared areas of geographic space

In the next example. We will create ten points randomly distributed across the Earths surface. Of the points that are on land, which countries are they in? using st_join

##Creating data frame of random ten points 
set.seed(2018) # set seed for reproducibility
(bb_world = st_bbox(world)) # the world's bounds
##       xmin       ymin       xmax       ymax 
## -180.00000  -90.00000  180.00000   83.64513
#>   xmin   ymin   xmax   ymax 
#> -180.0  -90.0  180.0   83.6
random_df = tibble(
  x = runif(n = 10, min = bb_world[1], max = bb_world[3]),
  y = runif(n = 10, min = bb_world[2], max = bb_world[4])
)
random_points = random_df %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y")) %>% # set coordinates
  st_set_crs(4326) # set geographic CRS
class(random_points)
## [1] "sf"         "data.frame"
#By default, st_join() performs a left join (see section 3.2.3), but it can also do inner joins by setting the argument left = FALSE

world$name_long = as.character(world$name_long)

world_random = world[random_points, ]
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
#subseting the points from world data to add different attributes to it 

#View(world_random)
random_joined = st_join(world_random, world["name_long"])
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
#View(random_joined)

plot(world["pop"], col = sf.colors(12, categorical = TRUE), border = 'grey', 
     axes = TRUE, reset = FALSE)
## Warning in plot.sf(world["pop"], col = sf.colors(12, categorical = TRUE), :
## col is not of length 1 or nrow(x): colors will be recycled; use pal to
## specify a color palette
plot(random_joined,pch = 3, add = TRUE, col = "red")
## Warning in plot.sf(random_joined, pch = 3, add = TRUE, col = "red"):
## ignoring all but the first attribute

###Only four points are on the land, They locate in Mexico, Morroco, Poland and Paraguay.

Non-overlapping joins within distance

In this example, two geographic datasets do not touch but still have a strong geographic relationship enabling joins. The datasets cycle_hire and cycle_hire_osm, already attached in the spData package.

plot(st_geometry(cycle_hire), col = "blue")
plot(st_geometry(cycle_hire_osm), add = TRUE, pch = 3, col = "red")

###Check if any points are in touch

any(st_touches(cycle_hire, cycle_hire_osm, sparse = FALSE))
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_touches assumes that they are planar
## [1] FALSE

Specifcying which points withing specific distance of each others

cycle_hire_P = st_transform(cycle_hire, 27700)
cycle_hire_osm_P = st_transform(cycle_hire_osm, 27700)
sel = st_is_within_distance(cycle_hire_P, cycle_hire_osm_P, dist = 20)
View(sel)
summary(lengths(sel) > 0)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE 
## logical     304     438

This shows that there are 438 points in the target object cycle_hire_P within the threshold distance of cycle_hire_osm_P

#Jioing the two datasets
z = st_join(cycle_hire_P, cycle_hire_osm_P, st_is_within_distance, dist = 20)
nrow(cycle_hire_P)
## [1] 742
#> [1] 742
nrow(z)
## [1] 762
#> [1] 762
View(z)

Note that the number of rows in the joined result is greater than the original file. This is because some cycle hire stations in cycle_hire_P have multiple matches in cycle_hire_osm_P

#check duplicates ID
n_occur <- data.frame(table(z$id))
#gives you a data frame with a list of ids and the number of times they occurred.

n_occur[n_occur$Freq > 1,]
##     Var1 Freq
## 131  134    2
## 246  253    2
## 459  482    4
## 461  484    8
## 484  510    6
## 580  613    4
#What are The duplicates IDs

The solution to the duplicates. Assuming that we care about the capacity variable we can aggregate Id variable and get the mean in term of capacity variable

z = z %>% 
  group_by(id) %>% 
  summarize(capacity = mean(capacity))
nrow(z) == nrow(cycle_hire)
## [1] TRUE

Alternatively removing duplicates rows in term of Id

z1 = z %>% distinct(id, .keep_all = TRUE)
nrow(z1) == nrow(cycle_hire)
## [1] TRUE

The distance between two objects is calculated with the st_distance()

#find the distance between the highest point in New Zealand and the geographic centroid of the Canterbury region.

nz_heighest = nz_height %>% top_n(n = 1, wt = elevation)
canterbury_centroid = st_centroid(canterbury)
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(canterbury): st_centroid assumes attributes are
## constant over geometries of x
st_distance(nz_heighest, canterbury_centroid)
## Units: [m]
##        [,1]
## [1,] 115540
